    <text>
        <body>
            <head>76. Information Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of State for Political and
                Military Affairs (<persName corresp="recWfOZtO0phY5iDk">Howe</persName>) and the
                Assistant Secretary of State for European Affairs (<persName
                    corresp="reccOrOPn6TsvnrGI">Burt</persName>) to Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d76fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SS_1">S/S</gloss> Special Handling
                    Restrictions Memos 1979–1983, Lot 96D262, Box 24, 1983 (CHRON BY WEEK, YR).
                    Secret; Sensitive. Drafted by Hall and Gordon; cleared by Dean and
                    Dobbins.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-08-10"
                        >August 10, 1983</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Basic Elements of the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                    and <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                    <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> Positions</item>
            </list>
            <p>This memorandum summarizes and compares the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >U.S.</placeName> and <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> positions as they stand at the end of Round IV of the negotia<pb
                    facs="0297" n="268" xml:id="pg_268"/>tions. It is designed as a companion piece
                to a separate paper<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d76fn2">Not further
                    identified.</note> which suggests how the two positions might be combined.</p>
            <p>In brief, the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> position
                focuses on achieving large reductions in <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>—to equal levels—and, by a
                network of constraints, on reducing the large <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                    >Soviet</placeName> missile <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >throw-weight</rs> advantage. With separate limits on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>, the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> seeks to protect our bomber
                capability and capture the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                <rs corresp="recbybjw3iHkqwwou" type="topic">Backfire bomber</rs> in the agreement.
                The <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> position places
                priority on <rs type="topic" corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">delivery vehicle</rs> (as
                in <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs>) and weapons
                limits, although they have yet to propose a specific ceiling on weapons. By
                providing an overall limit on <rs type="topic" corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">delivery
                    vehicles</rs>, insisting that there is no real difference between missiles and
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> (or their weapons) and
                refusing to discuss limits that would reduce <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF"
                    type="topic">throw-weight</rs>, they seek to protect their advantage in <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p>The following sections discuss the positions in terms of <hi
                    rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>, <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">delivery vehicles</rs> and <rs
                        corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>
                </hi>. Attached are charts describing the current balance and comparing the two
                positions to <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs>.<note n="3"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d76fn3">Attached but not printed are two charts:
                    “Comparison of <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> Proposals” and “The 1983 <rs type="topic" corresp="rec4magYO3Xg02IU4"
                        >Strategic Balance</rs>, July 1983.”</note>
            </p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">WARHEADS</rs>
            </p>
            <p>The <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                </gloss> has proposed to aggregate all <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04"
                    >ballistic missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">re-entry vehicles</rs> (<gloss
                    target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                </gloss>), <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss>, and bomber weapons—<rs type="topic" corresp="recnvEYOcmY68IH3z">gravity
                    bombs</rs>, <gloss target="#t_SRAM_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recJJ92wdIeZoqUpd">SRAMs</rs>
                </gloss>—into a (so-far unspecified) single limit on nuclear weapons. The purpose of
                this aggregate limit is to force the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >U.S.</placeName> to give up <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04"
                    >ballistic missile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                </gloss> in return for our bomber weapons and any <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> we wish to deploy.</p>
            <p>The central feature of the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> position has been a separate limit of 5000 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> along with a <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> of 2500 on <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                </gloss>, aimed at the <rs type="topic" corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic
                    systems</rs> with the greatest first-strike potential. We also have offered to
                limit <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> at a level lower than in <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs>, but we have
                rejected the Soviets’ attempt to combine armaments for slow-flying systems with
                those of <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>.</p>
            <p>In sum, the main <hi rendition="simple_italic">weapon limits</hi> in each proposal
                are:</p>
            <table cols="2">
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                            <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• Limit of <hi rendition="simple_italic">X</hi> on sum of:</cell>
                    <cell>• Limit of 5000 on missile <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>—Missile <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>—<rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 2500 <gloss
                            target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>—<gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>—Other Bomber Weapons</cell>
                    <cell>• Limit of 20 <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                        </gloss> per bomber</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <pb facs="0298" n="269" xml:id="pg_269"/>
            <p>The key difference between the proposals is the issue of aggregation. The Soviets
                insist that a weapon is a weapon; the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >U.S.</placeName> points out that <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                    >bombers</rs>, unlike missiles, must face unconstrained <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recY4zdE5fZQUvoyu">air defenses</rs> and therefore we
                cannot equate a gravity bomb to a missile <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                </gloss>. There are, also, important <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >verification</rs> issues with bomber weapons. Other important issues related to
                limits on weapons include:</p>
            <p>—The Soviets have told us that the 2500 <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19"
                    >sublimit</rs> on <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                </gloss> is unacceptable since it would force them to massively restructure their
                forces. For our part, we could probably drop the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> without consequence since under the
                5000 total <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                </gloss> ceiling the Soviets would reduce their <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> to somewhere in the 3000 <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                </gloss> range. However, if in the course of the negotiations the 5000 <gloss
                    target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                </gloss> limit is raised, we may wish to have such a <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs>. Moreover, it may prove to be of value
                as negotiating coin.</p>
            <p>—We will eventually need to refine the <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                </gloss> limit we have proposed. With no other restrictions on our <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>, we could theoretically deploy some
                7000 <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> (350 <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> x 20 <gloss
                    target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> per bomber). Yet our production plans only call for a buy of about 3000.
                And our plans through the early 1990s do not call for <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> to be deployed on more than about 200 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>. (We are therefore considering limits
                that are closer to our actual requirements, such as 200 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> × 20 <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> per bomber.)</p>
            <p>—While the Soviets have not tabled their specific weapon limit, we would expect it to
                be in the range of 11,000 or so deployed weapons on all <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic systems</rs>.</p>
            <p>The <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> positions also differ
                significantly with respect to <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss>. The Soviets have told us that their willingness to limit rather than ban
                    <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> is conditional upon our agreeing to ban <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss> (and <gloss target="#t_GLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recEYJpmEGRfvJpPc" type="topic">GLCMs</rs>
                </gloss>) of greater than 600 km range. The <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL"
                    >U.S.</placeName> has offered no <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> position in Geneva (we respond to <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> questions by asking the Soviets how they would verify their proposed ban).
                Development of a <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> position on
                    <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> limits is a high priority task in the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> community.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">DELIVERY VEHICLES</rs>
            </p>
            <p>The central feature of the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                position is a set of interlocking limits on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> and <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs> launchers. The structure is
                that of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs>, although the
                numbers are somewhat smaller, in line with the Soviets’ proposal to decrease the
                overall limit on missiles and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                    >bombers</rs> to 1800 from the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs> level of
                2250.</p>
            <p>The chief problem with such a framework is that it aggregates <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, potentially the most
                destabilizing systems, with slow-flying systems which we consider unsuitable for a
                    <rs corresp="recvZDidU8pZ1fdw1" type="topic">first strike</rs> and <pb
                    facs="0299" n="270" xml:id="pg_270"/> therefore far less threatening. We also
                have argued that the 1800 overall limit is not low enough, although in the round
                just past we have indicated our willingness to raise that number. This brings our
                position closer to the Soviets’ and accommodates the <orgName
                    corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">Scowcroft Commission</orgName>’s recommendation that
                    <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> give way to larger numbers of smaller, single-<gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                </gloss> missiles.</p>
            <p>The basic provisions related to <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">delivery vehicles</rs>
                </hi> are:</p>
            <table cols="2">
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                            <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 680 on
                            <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                        </gloss> launchers</cell>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 1080 on
                            <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBM</rs>
                        </gloss> launchers + <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">MIRVed</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                        </gloss> launchers</cell>
                    <cell>• Limit of 850–1250 deployed missiles</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 1200 on
                            <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                            <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> + above</cell>
                    <cell>• Limit of 400 (actually 350) <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE"
                            >bombers</rs>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• Limit of 1800 on total missiles and <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs>
                    </cell>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>While we have not offered an alternative to our original 850 limit on <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, it is
                generally understood that we will accept anything up to approximately 1250. This
                plus 400 <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bombers</rs> (350 is nearer
                our bottom line) would give a total of 1650 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recMGkwDnbHpEWvfN">delivery vehicles</rs>, close to the <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> number of 1800. Closing the gap
                would require more than just splitting the difference, however, since the question
                of aggregation separates the two positions.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">THROW-WEIGHT</rs>
            </p>
            <p>The <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> seeks to reduce the great
                disparity in <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> arising
                from the large <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> force of
                medium and heavy land-based <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. We have tabled a series of specific restrictions on both heavy and medium
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> which are designed to reduce <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                    >Soviet</placeName>
                <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> to the 2.5 million
                kilogram range (down from their current 5.6 Mkg and above the 1.9 of the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>). In the recently tabled <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> draft treaty, however, we left the
                provisions blank, telling the Soviets that we were flexible on the means of
                achieving the desired reductions.</p>
            <p>The Soviets, on the other hand, wish to retain maximum flexibility to structure their
                forces. They have rejected <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >throw-weight</rs> as a strategic indicator of any major significance.</p>
            <pb facs="0300" n="271" xml:id="pg_271"/>
            <p>The basic provisions related to <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >throw-weight</rs> are:</p>
            <table cols="2">
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">
                            <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">USSR</placeName>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• Future <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                        </gloss> limited to one “light” type only</cell>
                    <cell>• Ban on future heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>• No increase in silo volume or conversion of light <gloss
                            target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                        </gloss> launchers to heavy</cell>
                    <cell>• <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 110 heavy
                            <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d76fn4">To demonstrate flexibility, these
                                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> were not
                            included in <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                            draft treaty. [Footnote is in the original.]</note>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>• <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sublimit</rs> of 210 on
                        medium <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                        </gloss> + heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                            <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                        </gloss>
                        <note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d76fn5">To demonstrate flexibility, these
                                <rs corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19" type="topic">sublimits</rs> were not
                            included in <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                            draft treaty. [Footnote is in the original.]</note>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>• <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RV</rs>
                        </gloss> weight limit on new missiles</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>• Limit of 5000 ballistic missile <rs type="topic"
                            corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>With regard to <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>, the
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> positions have no commonality
                other than that the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs> limits would have
                the same effect as our proposed ban on new heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. They have rejected our “collateral constraints” on heavy and medium <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> as well as our suggestion that these limits could be replaced with direct
                limits on <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>. They have
                also rejected all limits which would explicitly reduce the number of <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky">SS–18s</rs> below current levels. Since
                the <rs type="topic" corresp="rec0tfPbYHg7imwab">Intelligence Community</rs>
                believes the Soviets will, in the future, emphasize <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recdBW6E9ogkYvqAR">SS–19</rs> class missiles (comparable to the <gloss
                    target="#t_MX_2">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M–X</rs>
                </gloss>) rather than heavy <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> and the Soviets themselves have indicated that the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky">SS–18s</rs> will eventually reach the end of their
                useful life, the <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                insistance on no <rs corresp="recAug8nb5QfVfzky" type="topic">SS–18</rs> limits
                (beyond those in <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM">II</rs>) may be an
                attempt to preserve negotiating capital.</p>
            <p>As you know, however, the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_IG_1">IG</gloss>’s <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic"
                    >throw-weight</rs> study has shown that the most important limit on the
                    <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs> is the 5000 ceiling
                on <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="rec3jfDwQdQCBVT9H">RVs</rs>
                </gloss>. This, combined with the <rs type="topic" corresp="rec0tfPbYHg7imwab"
                    >Intelligence Community</rs>’s initial view that the Soviets are themselves
                moving toward lower <rs corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF" type="topic">throw-weight</rs>
                systems may mean that our differences can be eventually resolved.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
